    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "03aa0eed_ff740a50",
        "filename": "util/linux/ptrace_requests.cc",
        "patchSetId": 20
      },
      "lineNbr": 90,
      "author": {
        "id": 1172779
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-05-16T17:11:03Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "FloatContext::f32::vfp will also have 4 bytes of padding on 64-bit.",
      "parentUuid": "47857816_2d654743",
      "revId": "86ccb582c47070c865ada7ba998609af66e43cae",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "40353740_b185daa0",
        "filename": "util/linux/ptrace_requests.cc",
        "patchSetId": 20
      },
      "lineNbr": 107,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-05-15T18:40:15Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "It’d be nice if we operated on an object that had {pid, bitness} so that we could just try the bitness operation that we know is right. That object could also have the ScopedPtraceAttach, which would encourage proper API usage. Then we could also replace GetRegistersResult with an easier-to-hold bool. What do you think?",
      "revId": "86ccb582c47070c865ada7ba998609af66e43cae",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "24308d7e_63f3c6fb",
        "filename": "util/linux/ptrace_requests.cc",
        "patchSetId": 20
      },
      "lineNbr": 107,
      "author": {
        "id": 1172779
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-05-16T17:11:03Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Yeah, I think it would definitely simplify parts of this.\n\nSomething like:\n\nclass ThreadInfo? or ThreadTrace?\n  bool Initialize(pid): Does a ptrace-attach, with same lifetime as object\n  bool Is64Bit(*is_64_bit)\n  bool GetGPRs(*context)\n  bool GetFPRs(*context)\n  bool GetThreadArea(*address)\n private:\n  ScopedPtraceAttach attachment;\n  bool is_64_bit_\n\nwhere return values indicate success/failure. GetGPRs is called internally before any other calls to determine bitness if needed.\n\nor\n\nclass ThreadInfo/ThreadTrace\n  bool Initialize(pid): Attaches just for the scope of Initialize and pre-ptraces all the return values\n  bool Is64Bit() const\n  ThreadContext* GetGPRs() const\n  FloatContext* GetFPRs() const\n  bool GetThreadArea(*address) const\n private:\n  is_64_bit_\n  thread_context_\n  float_context_\n  tls_address_\n  tls_address_initialized_\n\nThe second option more resembles ProcessInfo and fits with how I expect to use it in ProcessReader. GetThreadArea keeps the bool return condition for 64-bit tracing 32-bit ARM. (x86 tracing x86_64 is solved because fs_base is given in the GPRs)\n\nThe first might be more flexible if we want more of these calls to be able to fail in the future, but it might also be problematic to keep the ScopedPtraceAttach around for the object\u0027s whole lifetime. It might be nice to be able to keep ThreadInfo around as the home for ThreadContext, etc, rather than copying them out.\n\nOr possibly:\n  bool Initialize(pid): Attaches, traces all data, detaches but only returns false if the attachment fails.\n  bool GetGPRs(**context) const\n  bool GetFPRs(**context) const\n  bool GetThreadArea(*address) const\n private:\n  thread_context_\n  thread_context_initialized_\n  float_context_\n  float_context_initialized_\n  tls_address_\n  tls_address_initialized_\n\nWhere each call returns true if the out-pointer is set successfully.\nThis allows failures on individual calls and avoids hanging onto the ScopedPtraceAttach.\n\nI think I\u0027m leaning towards the second option.",
      "parentUuid": "40353740_b185daa0",
      "revId": "86ccb582c47070c865ada7ba998609af66e43cae",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "c2c7351b_85e57e11",
        "filename": "util/linux/ptrace_requests.cc",
        "patchSetId": 20
      },
      "lineNbr": 107,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-05-16T17:34:14Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I think I like the first one best, although the second one is OK too.\n\nI’ve got a concern about maintaining the process suspended, though. When we attach to something with ptrace, does it suspend just the thread we’re attaching to, or does it suspend all threads in the process?\n\nIt’s best for our “snapshot” to be as self-consistent as possible. Ideally, we want for all of the threads to be sitting still at the same time. And we’ll want to do other things, like read the process’ memory, while everything’s suspended too.",
      "parentUuid": "24308d7e_63f3c6fb",
      "revId": "86ccb582c47070c865ada7ba998609af66e43cae",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "748b93d5_83f348d7",
        "filename": "util/linux/ptrace_requests.cc",
        "patchSetId": 20
      },
      "lineNbr": 107,
      "author": {
        "id": 1172779
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-05-16T18:14:00Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "PTRACE_ATTACH sends a SIGSTOP, but this thread says that SIGSTOP behaves differently for ptrace-attach: https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id\u003d159663\nI\u0027ll try it out and see.\n\nOther ptrace facts:\nPTRACE_DETACH sends a SIGCONT. I\u0027ll see if this behaves differently too.\nA thread cannot ptrace attach to other threads in its thread group (my plan for self-tracing is to spawn a tracer thread in a new thread group with clone, but haven\u0027t actually tested that this works either).\n\nIf we want to keep all the threads stopped with a long lived ptrace-attach, I think we\u0027ll need to either avoid using ScopedPtraceAttach in multiple places or make it reference counting.",
      "parentUuid": "c2c7351b_85e57e11",
      "revId": "86ccb582c47070c865ada7ba998609af66e43cae",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "8e48dc0a_2d2fd0fb",
        "filename": "util/linux/ptrace_requests.cc",
        "patchSetId": 20
      },
      "lineNbr": 107,
      "author": {
        "id": 1172779
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-05-17T23:25:33Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "PTRACE_ATTACH/DETACH sends signals to the target thread similarly to tgkill.\n\nTo get a consistent snapshot, though, we\u0027d still need to avoid detaching from any threads until the snapshot is complete.",
      "parentUuid": "748b93d5_83f348d7",
      "revId": "86ccb582c47070c865ada7ba998609af66e43cae",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
